Operationally, early malware families maintained limited automation. Campaign management required manual updates to wallet addresses or binaries. Infrastructure reuse was common, which made campaigns easier to track through shared wallets, domain registrations, or hosting providers. Persistence mechanisms relied on straightforward techniques such as registry autoruns, scheduled tasks, or startup folder shortcuts.

Stealth and evasion in early variants were minimal. Malware sometimes attempted simple CPU throttling or process renaming to avoid suspicion, but many miners ran at full capacity. Static signatures, known pool addresses, and recognizable binary fingerprints made them relatively easy for antivirus systems to detect. Obfuscation techniques were generally limited to packers or basic string encryption.

Modern (≈2017–Present) Malware Infrastructure
Modern crypto‑mining malware ecosystems are significantly more modular and automated. Campaign operators typically deploy loader frameworks that dynamically retrieve configuration, mining modules, and updates from distributed infrastructure. Rather than relying on a single C2 server, campaigns frequently leverage domain generation algorithms (DGAs), content delivery networks, compromised web servers, and legitimate cloud services for hosting payloads.

Mining components are commonly executed in memory or delivered as secondary payloads. Some campaigns deploy containerized miners inside compromised cloud or Kubernetes environments. Infrastructure orchestration is often automated through scripts or botnet management panels that dynamically rotate wallets, pools, or proxy servers.

Modern campaigns heavily employ mining proxies to aggregate connections from infected hosts. Instead of each host connecting directly to a public pool, traffic passes through attacker‑controlled proxies that obscure wallet attribution and simplify management. Encryption (TLS‑wrapped Stratum or custom encrypted channels) is widely used to hide mining traffic from network inspection.

Stealth and Evasion Evolution
Modern malware significantly expands stealth strategies. Techniques include process injection into trusted system processes, fileless execution via PowerShell or WMI, and reflective loading to avoid disk artifacts. Some families monitor CPU usage or user activity and dynamically throttle mining intensity to reduce detection.

Advanced evasion strategies also target analysis environments. Malware may detect virtual machines, debuggers, or sandbox environments before activating mining components. Others employ polymorphic packers or runtime code generation to evade signature‑based detection. Network evasion includes protocol mimicry, encrypted Stratum communications, or proxy‑based traffic aggregation.

