OS-specific differences were pronounced. Windows-based malware exploited well-documented but weakly protected structures (SSDT, IRP hooks), while Linux malware relied on syscall table overwrites or Loadable Kernel Modules (LKMs). macOS (then OS X) had comparatively limited targeting due to smaller attack surface and stricter driver signing even in earlier versions. Cross-platform abstraction was minimal; implementations were highly tailored to kernel versions and memory layouts.

Modern Implementations:
Contemporary system hooking has shifted toward indirect, less detectable interception techniques due to the introduction of kernel patch protection (e.g., PatchGuard), driver signing enforcement, and virtualization-based security. Direct kernel structure modification is significantly constrained, leading to increased reliance on user-mode hooking, callback registration mechanisms, and abuse of legitimate extensibility points.

